al Data\n\nUse the following text for your answer. Do not make anything up in your answer.\n\nText:\n-----Entities-----\nhuman_readable_id,title,description,degree\r\n3,GENERATIVE AI,\"Generative AI refers to a category of artificial intelligence technology capable of creating new content, including text, images, videos, code, data, and other forms of media, based on user input or training data. This type of AI is widely used in academic research, manuscript preparation, and publishing processes. However, its use is subject to specific disclosure requirements when employed in academic work, submissions, or research. Generative AI may introduce inaccuracies, biases, or other issues if not used responsibly, and certain aspects of its application are restricted in academic publishing, particularly in the preparation of manuscripts and peer review processes. Some publishers, such as Elsevier, have implemented restrictions on the use of Generative AI for substantially writing manuscripts. Despite these limitations, Generative AI remains a significant tool in academic contexts, often utilized for content creation, data generation, and other research-related tasks. Its integration into academic workflows continues to raise important questions about authorship, accountability, and ethical use in scholarly communication.\",24\r\n6,LLM,\"Large language models (LLMs) are a subset of AI technology capable of generating human-like text, and in some cases, images and other forms of content. They are used in various aspects of academic writing, research, and manuscript preparation, including tasks such as text generation, language improvement, grammar correction, and data creation. LLMs, such as ChatGPT or DALL-E, are considered a type of generative AI that can produce text, code, and other content based on prompts. Their use in academic contexts is subject to disclosure requirements, with specific guidelines varying by publisher. For instance, Elsevier restricts the use of LLMs from substantially writing manuscripts, while Emerald imposes restrictions on their use during the peer review process. Additionally, LLMs are often used for editing and enhancing written content but are generally not intended for generating original research data. The extent of disclosure required depends on the impact of the LLM on the manuscript, with some institutions mandating transparency when these tools are employed in academic work.\",15\r\n1,ASHA,\"An organization that publishes journals and has specific policies on the use of artificial intelligence in manuscripts\"\"\",2\r\n130,ATTRIBUTION,\"The practice of properly citing sources, ideas, or quotes in scholarly work, which is often lacking in Generative AI outputs\"\"\",1\r\n131,INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY RISK,\"A risk associated with Generative AI tools, where the use of these tools may lead to unauthorized reuse of input or output data, potentially infringing on authors' or publishers' rights\"\"\",1\r\n150,RESPONSE,\"The output generated by an LLM in response to a prompt, which should be documented in the manuscript or appendix\"\"\",1\r\n\n\n-----Relationships-----\nhuman_readable_id,source,target,description,rank\r\n10,GENERATIVE AI,AUTHOR,\"The author is responsible for the ethical and accurate use of generative AI tools in their academic work, including ensuring the originality and integrity of their submissions. Authors must disclose the use of generative AI in their manuscripts, reflecting a shared responsibility between authors and generative AI systems in maintaining scholarly standards and transparency.\",83\r\n96,LLM,AUTHOR,\"Authors use LLMs to generate hypotheses or create data for analysis in their papers, requiring proper citation and disclosure\",74\r\n12,GENERATIVE AI,AI TECHNOLOGY,\"Generative AI is a type of AI technology that can create content, such as text, images, or code, based on user input. As a subset of AI technology, it is designed to generate new and original outputs rather than